5a. Unconditioned reinforcer vs. Conditioned reinforcer. Source: Pressley, Chapter 7. Explanation: Both are used in Skinner's
theory of operant conditioning. An unconditioned reinforcer is a consequence that is naturally reinforcing, such as food, sex,
affection, or praise. On the other hand, a conditioned reinforcer is reinforcer that does not satisfy any biological need, but has
become reinforcing by being paired with unconditional reinforcers. Examples of unconditioned reinforcers would be stickers
for completing assignments, tokens in a token economy, or grades. Both conditioned and unconditioned reinforcers when
provided after a behavior has been performed will increase the likelihood that the behavior/operant response will be emitted in
the future. 
5b. Differential reinforcement of other behaviors (DRO). Source: Skinner in Pressley, Chapter 7. Explanation: DRO may be
used as an alternative to punishment in operant conditioning. DRO involves reinforcing an alternative and, in most cases,
incompatible behavior to the behavior which the teacher or behavior management technician is attempting to extinguish or
decrease the likelihood of. An example would be reinforcing pro-social behaviors such as sharing toys and getting along on
the playground for a child who has problems with aggression in play situations. 
5c. Self-Instructional approaches to Self-Regulation. Source: Meichenbaum in Pressley Chapter 7. Explanation:
Meichenbaum argues that self-verbalizations are important in the cognitive behavior of children. They serve the purpose of
organizing complex behaviors. Explicit instruction to self-verbalize can help children to self-regulate their behavior, in
particular the inhibition of impulsive responses. 
5d. Social Learning Theory. Source: Bandura in Pressley Chapter 7. Explanation: The basic idea of Bandura's social learning
theory is that learning often occurs as a result of observing others performing behaviors and watching the reinforcement or
punishment others receive contingent on their behavior. Individual learn not only behaviors, but expectations of the
consequences by observing others. 
5e. Neo-Piagetian Theory of Development. Source: Case in Pressley, Chapter 7. Explanation: Case argues that practice frees
up space in short-term/working memory for the learning of more complicated tasks. Case believes that instruction should start
with a task that the child understands and can perform. Children should be made aware of how they perform these tasks and
be allowed to practice the tasks until they become automatized. Gradually, the teacher should increase the task demands
being careful to make sure that the demands of the more complicated tasks do not exceed the child's working memory
capacity. 
<br>
6. For my application of the key concepts I have chosen from Chapter 7 of Pressley, I will be teaching a social skills class for
sixth graders. I will use the SCORE curriculum which includes five microskills: S-sharing ideas, C-complimenting others,
O-offering help and encouragement, R-recommending changes nicely, and E-exercising self-control. To avoid overwhelming
the students and allow time to practice and master the skills, the classes will be spread over a seven-week span with one
hour-long class being held per week. The first week will be a general introduction to social skills and the necessity to learn
and use them in a variety of settings and situations. The next five sessions will each involve instruction in each of the skills.
Each skill will be divided into smaller, manageable steps that can be learned in isolation and then put together in a sequence
(Case's theory of development involving working memory capacity). The seventh week will be a summary of the five skills
and role plays that involve using more than one skill at a time. Classes will be limited to 10 students to provide more
opportunities for discussion and active role-playing of skills. Between social skills classes, students will be asked to record
instances in which either they performed or observed others performing the microskill for that week. 
<br>
For the first week, the introduction will include discussion on the importance of social skills and an explanation of the
terminology used in the lessons. Student will also be asked to rate their own performance on the behaviors to get an idea of
their general understanding of the microskills and their baseline use and confidence in performing the microskills prior to
instruction. The rating scales have proved useful in helping children reflect on their own behavior and become aware of areas
of both strength and weakness. Lastly, the instructor(s) will model an example of each of the microskills to give students a
frame of reference for the direction of future instruction. Additionally, students will be asked to look at both the verbal and
non-verbal (SEE- Smile, Eye contact and Expression) actions that make up social skills. 
<br>
The classes on the individual microskills will include an introduction to the skill, a modeling by the instructors of the skill, and
an analysis of the component skills and actions that make up the microskill. Students will be directed to look at both the
verbal and non-verbal components of the microskill. Students will discuss a variety of situations in which using the skills may
benefit them. Additionally, students will pair up and do role plays of three different situations in which they may use the skill.
Students will role play for each other to model the microskill and will be encourage to self-verbalize the steps involved. Role
plays will be followed by a review of the component skills used, in which students will identify the component parts of each
skill. (Meichenbaum's self-verbalization). 
<br>
Between class sessions students will be practicing the microskill of the week, along with recording instances of microskill
performance. In particular, children will be encouraged to self-verbalize the component steps of the microskill as they perform
the skill Classroom teachers will be encouraged to model (application of social learning theory) the microskills and point out
to the class when each skill has been used by a classmate (use of praise as a unconditioned reinforcer). Additionally, the
classroom teacher may set up a reinforcement system or token economy that rewards performance of the microskills in
collaborative instructional groups. Students may get sticker, candy, or additional free time for exhibiting social skills in class
(use of conditioned reinforcers). The teacher may also want to provide verbal feedback for students who do not use
microskills. This feedback would include call to the students attention instances in which one or more of the microskills may
have been appropriate and modeling an appropriate social response, using the social skills. By reinforcing pro-social
behaviors and calling to attention behaviors that are not pro-social, the teacher is increasing the use of social skills through
DRO and decreasing negative behaviors. 
<br>
