1. Lp533 2. 10-01-97 3. n/a 4. 10-01-97 5a. Equilibrium. Source: Pressley and lecture. Explanation: Equilibrium is a very
important mechanism for cognitive growth according to Piaget. When a situation occurs that destabilizes a belief we have (or
causes disequilibration), there is cognitive conflict. This motivates us to find a way to reconcile the new information or situation
with the beliefs we already have. The resolution of the cognitive conflict produces a new equilibrium. 5b. Cognitive Conflict.
Source: Pressley and lecture. Explanation: A state that occurs when the cognitive structures that had been perceived to work
are no longer perceived to be adequate. This triggers a process that often results in the construction of new cognitive
structures that help eliminate the conflict and brings us back to a state of equilibrium. 5c. Distinctive Features: Source:
Pressley and lecture. Explanation: Part of perceptual learning theory. The specific features that differentiate the members of a
class are distinctive only in relation to one another. Gibson1s theory is that adults are often quicker than children at perceptual
learning because their experiences have created an understanding of what to look for and what types of things constitute
distinctive features. 5d. Abstraction. Source: Pressley. Explanation: A basic mechanism of perceptual learning, according to
Gibson. Abstraction is the locating of distinctive features or invariant relationships (relationships that stay the same for a class
of events). 6. I am teaching a basic lesson on plants for middle school students. We begin with discussing what students
already know about plants. As we discuss plant nutrition, it1s very likely a number of students will say they think plants get
their food from the soil, the sun or perhaps water. I'll use a computer animation program to allow the students to do a few
simple experiments to explore how plants get food. As the students manipulate a limited number of variables, they will see that
a combination of factors are needed for plant nutrition. Their previously held beliefs on plant nutrition will likely be
destabilized, and they will experience cognitive conflict. The students will search for ways to produce equilibrium by
reconciling the new information with the beliefs they already have. The next portion of the lesson looks at some of the basic
types of plants. I'll have plants representing a variety of types in the classroom for the students to look at and touch. I'll ask
the students to discuss what features the plants have in common and what differences they see between the plants. This lesson
gives the students an opportunity to discover distinctive features and practice abstraction. 
