===message:1. Apprenticeship -(Pressley, p182) Vygosky's Approach to Mind.  People learn special skills by being around an expert in that field as an apprentice.  It is a powerful approach to instruction that should be used with school aged children to tackle reading, writing and arithmatic.  Situation cognition- Students’ understanding of the concepts they are learning are usually tied to the environment in which they've learn it.  This is a problem because these skills learned must be applied in many other environments.  Learning environments such as schools should be made like the real world so that the learned skills can be applied everywhere.  Apprentices observe others in the field in which they are learning; receive coaching from their mentors; and they practice their task that are expected of them. The components of apprenticeships are: modeling, coaching, scaffolding, articulation, reflection, and exploration. 

2. Reciprocal teaching-(Rosenshine (1979),  in Pressley, p189)   Instruction of comprehension strategies in reading groups.  Teacher models and explains multiple models understanding what has been read.  Students are taught to make predictions when reading,  question themselves  about the text, to seek clarification when confused and to summarize the content.  The students eventually internalize use of the four strategies in reciprocal teaching an they used them in the student groups as they continuously reason about the text.  The teacher becomes less involved as the students continuously go through this process.   

3. Direct Instruction:  (Duffy and Roehler in Pressley, p193). Content is very important and amount of time spent measures achievement (Rosenshine 1979).  It involves clear specifications  of goals  to the student and allows sufficient time for instruction with continuous, extensive coverage of the content.  Student’s performance is monitored and questions are asked at a level that students can handle them.  Feedback is provided that is academically oriented. 

4. Direct Explanation  (Pressley, p194). Retains many of the best features of direct instruction. It is process oriented.  Teacher models the strategies for children and children model them for teachers with feedback.  Long term transfers occur when instructions  include when and where to use the strategies being taught as well as opportunities to practice the strategies and applying them to many situations.  

EXAMPLES.  To practice and encourage writing in a first and second grade class we use journaling.  Initially, before each session the students gather around the teacher with an enlarged notepad that sits on an easel.  [Direct Explanation Modeling] The teacher begins her journal in front of the entire class.  She begins by asking what the beginning of a sentence should begin with.  (The students remember it should begin with a capital letter.) As she continues she emphasizes spacing between each word, the 3 different forms of the word "to", how to close a sentence with a period which lead to beginning a new sentence with a capital, etc  emphasizing strategies and coaching].   The teachers talks about these rules in writing as if the students already know this and they are just reminding her.  She also allows the students to give feedback to her writing process.  This serves as the students practice piece before they do their own journals.  She talks about how easy it is to come up with something to write because things happen everyday in our lives.  She writes about dinner she had at her parents home over the weekend.  She tells in detail about the meal, the preparation, the dessert, and then leaves it up to the children to guess how the evening ended.  She then explains in detail the strategies (a component in reciprocal teaching) she wants the students to use as they decided the best ending for the story.   They must clearly understand the events of the evening to get to an ending.  They are to answer questions about the story before coming up with an ending.  After this exercise the children began their individual journals.  

[Articulation] The children helps her to spell out "difficult" words (but the kids are using inventive spelling) and the teacher guides them (as needed) to spelling it correctly by adding letters that are missing or misplaced   While adding these letters she subtlely hints or reminds them of rules such as the "e" being silent or that they "y" sometimes has the "e" sound.  

[Reflection and mental modeling] After every few sentences, the teacher reminds the children that it is very important to read [aloud] what you have written after every one or two sentences just to make sure it makes sense.  She does this with her own journal entry.  This allows them to reflect on their writing skills and the writing process.    

[Exploration] After the teacher completes her journal entry, the student retrieve their journal and finds a comfortable place to begin writing.  The students are then allowed to apply the strategies of the writing process and the strategies in the content of their writing to their journal entry.  They are monitoring product as well as process.  The teacher reinstructs and re-explains as needed.

[Reciprocal Teaching] After reading the teachers completed journal, the children join their reading groups to discuss the content of the journal.  One student is assigned the role of group leader in each group and (s)he begins to ask questions about the event.  "What did Ms. E's parents cook for dinner?  Which night did she eat with her parents?  What was for dessert?" Finally to predict an ending to the story, the leader asks "what did they do after dinner?  Together they come up with suggestions.  The leader asks questions after the each suggestion to see if it makes sense or if it is possible.  The teacher walks around listening to each group and answers questions the students have about the process of the assignment.  At this point the teacher is less involved as the students interact with each other.  

[Direct Instruction] For the individual journaling task,  teacher allows children two 45 minute periods so that they may have time to complete each entry.  Teacher understands that at their skill level, it takes much longer for 1st and 2nd graders to write.  This also allows the teacher to have time to give feedback to each student.  Parents come in voluntarily to help students who are slower learners or are mechanically slower in the writing process.  This enables the needs of the children to be directly met.  These students work one on one or 2:1 with a volunteer.  The students who are faster at reading and writing can then begin to create story boards to match their journal entries.  



